# epic-harness Context

## Session Start

At the beginning of every session:
- Read `.harness/memory/` for project-specific rules and patterns
- If `.harness/sessions/*.json` exists, read the latest file for previous session context (resume state)
- Report any evolved skills found in `.harness/evolved/` — list their names and descriptions
- Run `epic-harness resume` if the binary is available: `command -v epic-harness && epic-harness resume`

Note: Cursor does not expose a session-start hook. This rule provides equivalent always-on context that achieves the same result.

## Auto-Behaviors

The following skills activate automatically based on context signals:

| Signal | Skill Triggered |
|--------|----------------|
| Auth, session, token, password, permissions code | `secure` checklist |
| Database query, ORM, SQL, migration code | `secure` + `perf` checklist |
| File exceeds 200 lines | `simplify` skill |
| Test failure encountered | `debug` skill (diagnose root cause before retrying) |
| Before marking any task complete | `verify` skill (build + test + lint) |
| New feature or bug fix | `tdd` skill (write test first) |

## Harness Memory

Always consult `.harness/memory/` before starting work. These files contain:
- Project-specific coding patterns and conventions
- Known pitfalls and anti-patterns for this codebase
- Cross-session learnings from the evolution engine

## Evolved Skills

If `.harness/evolved/` contains skill directories, treat them as supplementary guidance.
Static skills (tdd, secure, verify, simplify, perf, debug) always take priority over evolved skills.
Evolved skills extend, not replace, built-in behaviors.

## Snapshot on Completion

When a significant task is complete, run:
```
epic-harness snapshot
```
This preserves session state for future resume.
